00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:16,711
Each item will appear in several major
magazines during the month of July.

217
00:19:16,840 --> 00:19:20,628
As an example of our confidence
in the success of these new fashions...

218
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:25,709
...Ampco will be sending these lovely
models on a one-month tour...

219
00:19:25,840 --> 00:19:28,354
Sonny. I'd like you to say hello to Carol.

220
00:19:28,480 --> 00:19:29,913
Hey. How are you?

221
00:19:31,080 --> 00:19:32,559
Well, then let's...

222
00:19:35,160 --> 00:19:37,116
Carol's interested in commercials...

223
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:40,596
Hey, Sonny, I wanna get my son a horse.
What kind is best?

224
00:19:40,720 --> 00:19:42,950
- How old is your kid?
- He's six years old.

225
00:19:43,080 --> 00:19:44,957
Get him a short horse.

226
00:19:45,080 --> 00:19:49,198
- Hey, Hallie Martin. We met in New York.
- Did we like each other?

227
00:19:49,320 --> 00:19:52,551
That question about the merger -
who the hell was that guy?

228
00:19:52,680 --> 00:19:57,071
That was Cross, the Washington bureau
of the <i>Times</i>. He's connected to Treasury.

229
00:19:57,200 --> 00:19:59,430
- He shouldn't have been here.
- Spilt milk.

230
00:19:59,560 --> 00:20:03,712
Sonny, here's a couple I'd
like you to meet. Mr and Mrs Phillips.

231
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:06,513
- Hi.
- Steve Phillips, the Million-Dollar Club.

232
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:09,552
Sold a million dollars' worth
of Ranch Breakfast last year.

233
00:20:09,680 --> 00:20:13,309
- Well, the mean-question lady.
- I'm just curious.

234
00:20:13,440 --> 00:20:17,797
- Uh, Steve Phillips, the...
- You know what curiosity did to the cat.

235
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:22,436
He sold a million dollars' worth
of Ranch Breakfast last year. Wholesale.

236
00:20:22,560 --> 00:20:25,472
Are you kiddin' me? That's just fantastic.

237
00:20:25,600 --> 00:20:29,195
- We're very proud of it.
- I'll bet you are. And I am too. Damn.

238
00:20:29,320 --> 00:20:31,993
- I just love that...
- This is Grace Phillips.

239
00:20:32,120 --> 00:20:35,192
I know. We met too.
Everything's going around and around.

240
00:20:35,320 --> 00:20:39,279
- Oh, that poster is beautiful.
- It's a great gimmick. Very effective.

241
00:20:39,400 --> 00:20:44,474
Grace, why don't you stand in front of it
with Sonny, and Steve can take a picture.

242
00:20:44,600 --> 00:20:48,513
Why not just take a picture of Grace in
front of that picture of me and the box...

243
00:20:48,640 --> 00:20:51,473
...with a picture of me on the box,
holding a picture of me...

244
00:20:51,600 --> 00:20:55,149
Then you got Grace
and a whole bunch of pictures of me.

245
00:20:55,960 --> 00:21:00,272
Sonny, you know that TV show in Denver?
We've had to make changes in your copy.

246
00:21:00,400 --> 00:21:02,550
I bet it's shorter.

247
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:06,477
- In a multimedia situation...
- Mr Sears?

248
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:10,398
Hello, Sonny. It's about time
we finally met, isn't it?

249
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:13,956
- Yes, sir, it's about time.
- Everybody here know Mr Steele?

250
00:21:14,080 --> 00:21:16,799
Like our horse?
Couldn't have a better straight man.

251
00:21:16,920 --> 00:21:19,514
- Can I have a word with you, sir?
- Perhaps later.

252
00:21:19,640 --> 00:21:23,110
- Beautiful animal, isn't it?
- Yes, sir, he's an amazing animal.

253
00:21:23,240 --> 00:21:26,630
But he don't belong
in a parking lot in Las Vegas.

254
00:21:26,760 --> 00:21:31,276
I don't suppose Las Vegas is the most
natural place in the worid for any of us.

255
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:34,800
Well, sir, I don't think he's feelin' so good.

256
00:21:34,920 --> 00:21:37,115
Let's give him a drink!

257
00:21:37,240 --> 00:21:39,993
Rising Star represents
a substantial investment.

258
00:21:40,120 --> 00:21:43,192
You can be sure
we've entrusted his care to experts.

259
00:21:43,320 --> 00:21:46,756
Well, I don't think
them experts are so expert.

260
00:21:47,360 --> 00:21:52,957
Mr Steele, would you please sign this
picture for me? For my daughter Tammy.

261
00:21:55,240 --> 00:21:58,550
Look, why don't I make an appointment
with Mr Sears's secretary...

262
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:01,797
Why would you put that horse
on a stage with dancing girls?

263
00:22:01,920 --> 00:22:04,388
- Just a minute...
- I'm talkin' to <i>him</i>.

264
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:09,389
It sells products, Sonny.

265
00:22:09,520 --> 00:22:14,753
You mustn't apply logic to advertising.
It'll just confound you, believe me.

266
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:17,917
Well, it just don't feel right to me.
It seems wrong.

267
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:21,157
All them lights blinkin' and winkin',
and girls...

268
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:23,475
Sir, I used to rodeo.

269
00:22:25,360 --> 00:22:27,828
- And I was good at it.
- That's irrelevant.

270
00:22:30,840 --> 00:22:32,159
To who?

271
00:22:32,280 --> 00:22:34,999
This is a conversation
we might have some other time.

272
00:22:35,120 --> 00:22:35,996
Would it matter?

273
00:22:36,120 --> 00:22:39,430
What matters is that you fulfil
the requirements of your contract.

274
00:22:39,560 --> 00:22:43,473
Which don't include your passing
judgment on corporate policy.

275
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:46,998
Nothin' in that contract
about me ridin' toy horses.

276
00:22:47,120 --> 00:22:49,429
You're not in rodeo any more.

277
00:22:49,560 --> 00:22:51,835
Actually, you're more famous now,
aren't you?

278
00:22:51,960 --> 00:22:55,635
Your face is on millions of boxes,
on billboards all over the country...

279
00:22:55,760 --> 00:22:57,955
...people want your autograph...

280
00:22:58,080 --> 00:23:01,117
What I'm talking about
is that you voluntarily accepted...

281
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:04,152
...a highly paid, relatively simple job...

282
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:08,910
...that more than a handful of cowboys
would give their right arm for.

283
00:23:10,480 --> 00:23:12,118
You're right.

284
00:23:12,240 --> 00:23:14,674
I don't want just to be right.

285
00:23:15,960 --> 00:23:19,555
- You want me to like it?
- It would be a factor in our relationship.

286
00:23:19,680 --> 00:23:23,150
Mr Sears, Joanna Camden
is waiting over by the earthmover.

287
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:26,397
- Why don't we have a picture session?
- Excuse us, please.

288
00:23:26,520 --> 00:23:28,636
You bet.

289
00:23:28,760 --> 00:23:32,389
- I'm sorry, sir.
- When this is over, get rid of him.

290
00:23:58,800 --> 00:24:01,519
- Charlotta! Hey!
- Got a quarter?

291
00:24:01,640 --> 00:24:04,473
No, don't... don't say it.
I bet that cheque's in the mail.

292
00:24:04,600 --> 00:24:07,797
Wendell handles all that, babe,
you know that. Come talk to me.

293
00:24:07,920 --> 00:24:10,480
How <i>is</i> old Wendell
who can't find a stamp?

294
00:24:10,840 --> 00:24:15,834
Bartender? Give us a double Jack Daniels,
please. Tall glass.

295
00:24:17,680 --> 00:24:21,514
- The lady will take a Rob Roy.
- Orangeade. I quit.

296
00:24:22,160 --> 00:24:25,516
What... What's the matter?
You're not born-again, are you?

297
00:24:25,880 --> 00:24:29,793
Maybe I am.
I got me a record contract now.

298
00:24:29,920 --> 00:24:32,673
All on my own too.
You be sure and tell Wendell Hixson <i>that</i>.

299
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:36,713
You sure are tough on Wendell. Not that
I blame you, cheques bein' late an' all.

300
00:24:36,840 --> 00:24:40,594
I don't wanna talk about the cheques.
You know what I wanna talk about.

301
00:24:40,720 --> 00:24:42,836
I want you to sign these papers.

302
00:24:42,960 --> 00:24:46,555
You don't think I saw you tryin'
to slip out? I left three messages.

303
00:24:46,680 --> 00:24:50,036
Well, now wait a minute.
I didn't get no messages.

304
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:55,629
Sonny, that judge told you
to sign the papers.

305
00:24:55,920 --> 00:25:01,711
- Don't you wanna be divorced for real?
- Yes, I do. I just... Well, I've been busy.

306
00:25:01,840 --> 00:25:05,515
Busy?! Doin' what? Makin' up excuses?

307
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:06,595
Excuses?

308
00:25:06,720 --> 00:25:10,713
You got somebody now who sits up
all night cos you lost your keys?

309
00:25:10,840 --> 00:25:12,478
Or you got a flat tyre?

310
00:25:12,600 --> 00:25:17,276
Comin' home at 6am, expectin' me
to cook breakfast for a dozen cowboys.

311
00:25:17,400 --> 00:25:21,393
And cowgirls who didn't bother to look
like they hadn't been in your back seat!

312
00:25:21,520 --> 00:25:24,239
Charlotta, yoo-hoo,
you got a mean memory.

313
00:25:24,360 --> 00:25:26,669
- Just a couple of parties...
- A couple?!

314
00:25:26,800 --> 00:25:29,394
That light-up suit
musta given you shock treatment!

315
00:25:29,520 --> 00:25:32,557
I'm talkin' a <i>lot</i> of parties,
and a <i>lot</i> of back seats!

316
00:25:32,680 --> 00:25:34,830
But for back seats, we'd never have met.

317
00:25:34,960 --> 00:25:37,110
And I'll bet you're still doin' it.

318
00:25:37,240 --> 00:25:39,674
Stayin' up all night, burnin' yourself out.

319
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:43,429
You're just walkin' around
to save funeral expenses.

320
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:46,435
You smile, babe. You get my insurance.

321
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:50,792
Do you know what your skeleton looks like
in them x-ray pictures? A junkyard.

322
00:25:50,920 --> 00:25:53,832
You couldn't get through
a metal detector stark naked.

323
00:25:53,960 --> 00:25:55,871
Give me the papers.

324
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:57,319
Huh?

325
00:25:57,440 --> 00:25:59,590
Give me the papers.

326
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:03,160
- For real?
- Give me them.

327
00:26:15,720 --> 00:26:17,870
You look like hell.

328
00:26:18,680 --> 00:26:20,955
Well, you look great.

329
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:25,796
Hey. Would you come up to my room?

330
00:26:26,240 --> 00:26:29,869
I can't. You just know what'd happen.

331
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:31,793
Yeah.

332
00:26:31,920 --> 00:26:34,388
Besides, I got somebody
who really likes me now.

333
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:36,750
Well, it's not hard to do.

334
00:26:37,320 --> 00:26:40,676
- Who's the lucky fella?
- Billy-Roy Fix.

335
00:26:42,080 --> 00:26:44,196
Billy-Roy Fix?

336
00:26:44,320 --> 00:26:46,276
Is that right?

337
00:26:47,040 --> 00:26:50,077
I guess there's just somethin'
about us Western stars.

338
00:26:50,200 --> 00:26:55,115
- <i> Mr Sonny Steele, please report</i>...
- Oop, that's me. I'm late.

339
00:26:58,840 --> 00:27:00,796
Goodbye, darlin'.

340
00:27:02,640 --> 00:27:05,677
Bye, darlin'. Take care, huh?

341
00:28:16,400 --> 00:28:18,152
Well, Mr Steele.

342
00:28:22,160 --> 00:28:25,675
After this number,
the motorcycle daredevils - God save us.

343
00:28:25,800 --> 00:28:28,109
And then you and the horse.

344
00:28:46,720 --> 00:28:50,838
Now, listen. You don't start those things
until I give you the cue, yes?

345
00:29:09,640 --> 00:29:11,471
Not now.

346
00:29:11,600 --> 00:29:13,955
Not now! Not now!

347
00:29:37,400 --> 00:29:39,755
Open the curtain.

348
00:30:13,520 --> 00:30:16,239
Forget the routine! Go right to the finale!

349
00:30:16,360 --> 00:30:19,750
That was very effective.
This is no criticism, you understand...

350
00:30:19,880 --> 00:30:22,519
...but it's too dangerous
to use that horse on a ramp.

351
00:30:22,640 --> 00:30:24,471
He wasn't supposed to be on the ramp!

352
00:30:24,600 --> 00:30:29,310
He wasn't even supposed to be out there
yet! He's ruined the whole concept!

353
00:30:37,080 --> 00:30:41,232
<i># I gotta run to keep from hidin'</i>

354
00:30:42,200 --> 00:30:45,909
<i># And I'm bound to keep on ridin'</i>

355
00:30:46,600 --> 00:30:51,628
<i># And I got one more silver dollar</i>

356
00:30:51,760 --> 00:30:53,716
<i># And I ain't gonna let 'em catch me</i>

357
00:30:53,840 --> 00:30:59,437
<i># No, I ain't gonna let 'em catch</i>
<i>the midnight rider</i>

358
00:31:35,280 --> 00:31:38,431
- What did he say?
- He was rude. He was very rude!

359
00:31:38,560 --> 00:31:41,791
- And he wasn't concentrating.
- He must've said something to you.

360
00:31:41,920 --> 00:31:45,629
Well, he was askin' about
the horse's tendon, and the drugs.

361
00:31:45,840 --> 00:31:49,276
Drugs? What drugs?

362
00:31:49,920 --> 00:31:52,912
- Well, the tranquillisers and...
- That's done all the time.

363
00:31:53,040 --> 00:31:55,315
They tranquillise the animal
to keep it calm.

364
00:31:55,440 --> 00:31:58,432
And the Butazolidin
they use for the... tendon.

365
00:31:58,560 --> 00:32:01,199
Mutual Indemnity and the police.
Which do you want?

366
00:32:01,320 --> 00:32:04,437
- Neither. I wanna keep this quiet.
- You may as well know the rest.

367
00:32:04,560 --> 00:32:09,429
Sonny knows horses. I think he's guessed
we've used steroids to muscle him up.

368
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:12,075
Well, are they dangerous?

369
00:32:12,920 --> 00:32:15,036
Well, they make the horse sterile.

370
00:32:15,160 --> 00:32:19,517
Well, temporarily. I mean, it's just
a side effect. It's not a permanent thing.

371
00:32:19,640 --> 00:32:22,029
Do we put that on the box top,
"Temporary"?

372
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:26,597
- It goes away in, what, how many hours?
- Gentlemen, would you excuse us?

373
00:32:26,720 --> 00:32:29,996
- There are drinks upstairs.
- Ah, the worid of illusion.

374
00:32:31,200 --> 00:32:33,509
Just a minute, fellas. I'll be right out.

375
00:32:33,640 --> 00:32:35,596
Jesus...

376
00:32:38,040 --> 00:32:41,919
We're not talking about a horse,
we're talking about a $300 million merger.

377
00:32:42,040 --> 00:32:44,076
Omnibank will make a feast out of this.

378
00:32:44,200 --> 00:32:47,556
If Steele talks to anyone before
he's caught, we have no merger.

379
00:32:47,680 --> 00:32:49,955
Ampco and the horse are the same thing.

380
00:32:50,080 --> 00:32:53,436
If we've mismanaged the horse,
we've mismanaged the corporation.

381
00:32:53,560 --> 00:32:57,473
- Couldn't he have called the SPCA?
- What'll we say to the reporters?

382
00:32:57,600 --> 00:33:00,398
- Tell 'em to go to bed.
- It's a little late for that.

383
00:33:00,520 --> 00:33:02,875
And get those morons out of here.

384
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:06,231
- Come on, Bob.
- One drunken cowboy!

385
00:33:26,720 --> 00:33:29,393
We have been advised
by the attorney general...

386
00:33:29,520 --> 00:33:33,035
...that the theft of Rising Star
is grand larceny, a felony.

387
00:33:33,160 --> 00:33:38,280
Should this prove to be a deliberate act,
a warrant will be issued for Mr Steele.

388
00:33:38,400 --> 00:33:42,313
At this time, however, our primary concern
is the welfare of our horse.

389
00:33:42,440 --> 00:33:45,637
What did he say to Sears?
They were really goin' at each other.

390
00:33:45,760 --> 00:33:47,716
Hallie, give me a break, will ya?

391
00:33:47,840 --> 00:33:51,435
- Ransom. What about ransom?
- The man's not <i>that</i> crazy.

392
00:33:51,560 --> 00:33:55,712
He's been tossed on his head enough
times. Thought about brain damage?

393
00:33:55,840 --> 00:34:00,072
The cowboy is a little hot-tempered.
He's emotionally disturbed, that's all.

394
00:34:00,200 --> 00:34:04,751
Come on, Fitz. He's made a mistake
and he'll bring it back when he cools out?

395
00:34:04,880 --> 00:34:07,474
- Oh, come on.
- Look, let me alone, will ya?

396
00:34:07,600 --> 00:34:09,318
I don't know any answers.

397
00:34:09,440 --> 00:34:12,238
I don't know from brain damage,
from cooling out...

398
00:34:12,360 --> 00:34:16,239
Look, why don't you go have a sauna?
Give me some <i>good</i> news, for chrissake!

399
00:34:16,360 --> 00:34:18,476
"Cool... out."

400
00:34:28,840 --> 00:34:30,353
...<i>these days</i>.

401
00:34:30,480 --> 00:34:33,552
- <i> Why'd she quit him?</i>
- <i> Who knows?</i>

402
00:34:36,280 --> 00:34:40,398
<i>Sonny was married in Gus's living room</i>.
<i>And when that woman quit him,</i>...

403
00:34:40,520 --> 00:34:42,829
...<i>well, you know</i>
<i>where Sonny came to cool out</i>.

404
00:34:42,960 --> 00:34:45,918
<i>Course, Gus is gettin' old</i>
<i>and strange these da</i>...

405
00:34:48,160 --> 00:34:51,197
...<i>well, you know</i>
<i>where Sonny came to cool out</i>.

406
00:34:51,320 --> 00:34:53,880
<i>Course, Gus is gettin' old</i>
<i>and strange these days</i>.

407
00:35:16,800 --> 00:35:18,358
Seen Wendell?

408
00:35:18,480 --> 00:35:22,632
No. I haven't seen nobody. They're just
runnin' round like crazy people today.

409
00:35:22,760 --> 00:35:26,878
- Buy you a drink?
- No, thanks. I got one. That's my limit.

410
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:32,074
Hey, tell me somethin'. Somethin'
personal. Were you surprised he did it?

411
00:35:32,600 --> 00:35:34,158
Who, Sonny?

412
00:35:34,280 --> 00:35:37,829
Well, Sonny'll surprise ya. Just some
surprises are bigger than others.

413
00:35:37,960 --> 00:35:41,236
Like he gave me this ring one day,
just like that.

414
00:35:41,360 --> 00:35:43,749
Had old Wendell's teeth
fixed for him, too.

415
00:35:43,880 --> 00:35:46,633
- What's your last name?
- Smitley.

416
00:35:46,760 --> 00:35:49,320
Say, you know something?
We got a mutual friend.

417
00:35:49,440 --> 00:35:52,796
- Oh, we do? Well, who do we know?
- Gus Atwater.

418
00:35:53,440 --> 00:35:56,591
I know Gus. Do you know Gus?
Where do you know Gus from?

419
00:35:56,720 --> 00:36:01,589
Oh, sure. Wait, are we talkin' about
the same Gus, from, uh, Tuba City?

420
00:36:01,720 --> 00:36:06,475
No, not Tuba City. No, the Gus I mean
is from Mesquite, about 30 miles up here.

421
00:36:06,600 --> 00:36:07,476
Mesquite.

422
00:36:22,680 --> 00:36:25,035
You wanna drive?

423
00:36:52,720 --> 00:36:54,278
Morning.

424
00:36:54,400 --> 00:36:56,356
Hello.

425
00:36:57,920 --> 00:37:01,799
- You got any, uh, eucalyptus leaves?
- You must be a Capricorn.

426
00:37:05,800 --> 00:37:08,712
- You got any eucalyptus leaves?
- Just tea bags.

427
00:37:08,840 --> 00:37:11,752
- Well, I need some of them tea bags.
- How many would you like?

428
00:37:11,880 --> 00:37:13,359
Oh, five or six dozen.

429
00:37:13,480 --> 00:37:15,596
- Bags?
- Boxes.

430
00:37:19,040 --> 00:37:21,838
Come on, boy. Come on, son.

431
00:37:22,480 --> 00:37:27,270
Just a couple more times of doin' this
and you'll be breathin' just fine.

432
00:37:27,400 --> 00:37:29,391
If <i>I</i> live.

433
00:37:51,040 --> 00:37:54,953
- Mr Atwater?
- # Golden hills

434
00:37:55,240 --> 00:37:57,196
# Round her head

435
00:37:58,120 --> 00:38:01,317
# Glimmer golden hills

436
00:38:03,280 --> 00:38:05,191
Mr Atwater?

437
00:38:05,320 --> 00:38:07,276
You wounded?

438
00:38:07,760 --> 00:38:10,718
- No, I'm looking for a friend of ours.
- He ain't here.

439
00:38:11,160 --> 00:38:13,469
- But he was.
- Yep.

440
00:38:14,520 --> 00:38:16,750
From about this high.

441
00:38:18,440 --> 00:38:21,989
- Was he here today?
- Here today, gone tomorrow.

442
00:38:22,120 --> 00:38:24,315
Like a flutterin' bird.

443
00:38:25,520 --> 00:38:28,990
- Hey, hey, who are you?
- I work for television.

444
00:38:29,920 --> 00:38:32,275
- You know television?
- Yeah. I got one.

445
00:38:33,680 --> 00:38:36,114
Works sometimes. Comes a-flashin'.

446
00:38:36,240 --> 00:38:39,471
Woo-woo-woo-woo!

447
00:38:40,600 --> 00:38:43,956
- Gus, I'm a friend of Leroy's.
- Leroy! Oh-ho!

448
00:38:44,080 --> 00:38:47,550
Yeah. And, uh... and Wendell.

449
00:38:48,320 --> 00:38:51,073
They told me you'd know
where to find him.

450
00:38:53,000 --> 00:38:55,958
How else would I know
where you were? Huh?

451
00:38:58,440 --> 00:39:00,795
We're real worried about him.

452
00:39:00,920 --> 00:39:03,195
I gotta find him. I have to talk to him.

453
00:39:04,840 --> 00:39:07,035
I can't hurt him.

454
00:39:07,160 --> 00:39:10,596
He came here. Covered with a mist.

455
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:14,872
You know? Like floats atop a river?

456
00:39:15,640 --> 00:39:19,679
And... and it grows into a cloud...

457
00:39:20,600 --> 00:39:23,751
...and it shuts away the sun...

458
00:39:26,520 --> 00:39:27,635
Where'd he go, Gus?

459
00:39:31,840 --> 00:39:34,718
- No, please!
- What?! How did you find me?

460
00:39:34,840 --> 00:39:37,513
- What are you doing?
- You're hurting me! Stop it!

461
00:39:37,640 --> 00:39:39,073
- Who's with you?
- I'm alone.

462
00:39:39,200 --> 00:39:40,997
- How did you find me?
- I swear to God...

463
00:39:41,120 --> 00:39:43,429
- How did you get here?
- I drove myself.

464
00:39:43,560 --> 00:39:45,471
How? How did you find me?

465
00:39:46,600 --> 00:39:48,397
Gus.

466
00:39:49,680 --> 00:39:51,591
Gus Atwater.

467
00:39:51,720 --> 00:39:53,676
Gus?

468
00:39:58,560 --> 00:39:59,629
Gus.

469
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:02,116
Can I... can I get up now?

470
00:40:02,760 --> 00:40:04,910
Please?

471
00:40:05,040 --> 00:40:07,315
How did you know to get to Gus?

472
00:40:09,280 --> 00:40:12,556
I... interviewed your friends.

473
00:40:14,160 --> 00:40:15,639
Who?

474
00:40:15,760 --> 00:40:18,593
Wendell and Leroy. I figured they'd...

475
00:40:20,120 --> 00:40:23,317
Wait a minute, you hit my face,
you son of bitch!

476
00:40:23,800 --> 00:40:26,075
I'm not gonna stay here.

477
00:40:30,960 --> 00:40:33,349
What did you take the horse for?

478
00:40:34,120 --> 00:40:35,633
You're crazy.

479
00:40:35,760 --> 00:40:40,834
- Does anybody else know about Gus?
- No. No. And nobody knows anything...

480
00:40:40,960 --> 00:40:45,795
Oh, <i>I'm</i> crazy? You go off with somebody
else's $12 million horse, and <i>I'm</i> crazy?!

481
00:40:45,920 --> 00:40:47,717
- Hold it. Hold it.
- Don't you hit me!

482
00:40:47,840 --> 00:40:49,796
- Did you scare that old man?
- No.

483
00:40:50,400 --> 00:40:52,630
Does anybody else know you're here?

484
00:40:52,760 --> 00:40:57,880
No. Nobody knows anything. I don't have
any reason to tell anybody anything.

485
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:00,389
Go away. Go home.

486
00:41:03,400 --> 00:41:06,039
Well, what <i>are</i> you gonna do with him?

487
00:41:07,560 --> 00:41:13,510
Look, just tell me why you took the horse.
You can't race him. You can't sell him.

488
00:41:13,640 --> 00:41:17,189
And you're not gonna start
your own cereal company.

489
00:41:18,840 --> 00:41:21,274
I mean, what the hell <i>do</i> you want?

490
00:41:24,200 --> 00:41:27,192
Oh, can't you just answer one question?

491
00:41:27,800 --> 00:41:32,112
Look, I don't have anything against you.
I don't usually get hit doing this, but...

492
00:41:32,240 --> 00:41:34,754
What do you expect,
sneakin' up like some cat?

493
00:41:34,880 --> 00:41:37,599
I tried to call, but your line was busy.

494
00:41:41,320 --> 00:41:46,189
Do you know how worried your friends are
about you? Wendell and Leroy?

495
00:41:47,840 --> 00:41:50,593
Isn't there something I can tell them?

496
00:41:53,880 --> 00:41:56,678
What is this place?
Does this have special meaning to you?

497
00:41:56,880 --> 00:41:59,474
You want information, go to the library.

498
00:42:00,160 --> 00:42:03,311
I know what you want. It ain't answers.

499
00:42:03,440 --> 00:42:07,274
You just want a story. Any story.
Why don't you make one up?

500
00:42:07,400 --> 00:42:11,234
That's what you all do anyway.
You don't need me to tell you no story.

501
00:42:11,360 --> 00:42:15,114
You ask me why I'm 45 minutes late.
You're not interested in why I'm late.

502
00:42:15,240 --> 00:42:19,279
Just in gettin' a rise outta me. "Do I eat
Ranch Breakfast?" Who the hell cares?

503
00:42:19,400 --> 00:42:21,834
Honest to hell, you people
are all the same.

504
00:42:21,960 --> 00:42:24,235
There's folks in Africa,
or some damn place...

505
00:42:24,360 --> 00:42:26,794
...you try to take a picture of them,
they'll kill ya.

506
00:42:26,920 --> 00:42:30,629
They figure you're takin' somethin' from
them, and you just got so much stuff...

507
00:42:30,760 --> 00:42:33,274
...and if other people take it all
you got nothin' left.

508
00:42:33,400 --> 00:42:35,914
Well, I don't wanna be no story.

509
00:42:37,440 --> 00:42:41,991
- I've just retired from public life.
- Boy, have you got that wrong.

510
00:42:42,120 --> 00:42:45,829
You rode down the Las Vegas Strip
with somebody else's $12 million horse.

511
00:42:45,960 --> 00:42:49,270
Did you think we wouldn't notice?
You're a story all right.

512
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:51,595
But not yours.

513
00:42:56,040 --> 00:42:58,759
I'm nobody's story but my own now.

514
00:43:01,120 --> 00:43:04,396
But... Wait, wait a minute...
Where are you going?

515
00:43:05,640 --> 00:43:08,438
Oh, I hurt your feelings, didn't I?

516
00:43:09,400 --> 00:43:13,439
I didn't mean to hurt your feelings.
Was it something I said?

517
00:43:13,960 --> 00:43:16,428
Look, can't you just do
a working girl a favour?

518
00:43:16,560 --> 00:43:19,950
I'm just trying to earn an honest buck,
tell an honest tale.

519
00:43:20,080 --> 00:43:22,992
I don't want to make up
a story about you.

520
00:43:23,120 --> 00:43:25,395
Anyway, what have you got to lose?

521
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:29,195
Everybody's wondering where you're going,
why you did it.

522
00:43:29,640 --> 00:43:32,791
The great American cowboy
and the worid-champion horse...

523
00:43:32,920 --> 00:43:34,273
...riding into the sunset...

524
00:43:34,400 --> 00:43:38,188
Boy, are you full of shit.
With all due respect, ma'am.

525
00:43:38,320 --> 00:43:41,596
- And you're standin' in poison sumac.
- Oh!

526
00:43:43,840 --> 00:43:46,070
Come on, son. Come on, boy.

527
00:43:48,120 --> 00:43:52,511
If you think you're gettin' away from me
you're not, cos I'm gonna follow you.

528
00:43:52,640 --> 00:43:57,316
I'm gonna follow you till you tell me
what you're gonna do with the horse.

529
00:44:01,040 --> 00:44:03,190
What are you doing?

530
00:44:04,120 --> 00:44:05,997
Oh, my God!

531
00:44:06,120 --> 00:44:09,874
Now it shouldn't take you more
than about 15 minutes to change that.

532
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:13,788
Goddamn you! You're nuts! I'm gonna call
the cops. I got your license plate.

533
00:44:13,920 --> 00:44:15,194
- No, you won't.
- Yes, I will.

534
00:44:15,320 --> 00:44:19,677
No, you won't. I know what you'll do.
You'll milk this story for all it's worth.

535
00:44:19,800 --> 00:44:24,635
You don't want me to be captured.
A captured horse thief ain't no story.

536
00:44:27,960 --> 00:44:32,431
It was from this hotel that Rising Star,
greatest money-winner in racing history...

537
00:44:32,560 --> 00:44:36,189
...and corporate symbol for one
of the worid's largest conglomerates...

538
00:44:36,320 --> 00:44:38,311
...was taken late Friday night.

539
00:44:38,440 --> 00:44:42,638
Yesterday I uncovered information
which allowed me to locate Sonny Steele.

540
00:44:43,280 --> 00:44:46,158
<i> Now to raise</i>
<i>the old Stars and Stripes</i>.

541
00:44:46,280 --> 00:44:48,714
<i>Where's that blasted flagpole?</i>

542
00:44:48,840 --> 00:44:51,434
<i>Good gracious! A bird's nest!</i>

543
00:44:51,920 --> 00:44:56,118
<i>How clumsy of me. I hope</i>
<i>I didn't step on your eggs, birdie</i>.

544
00:44:57,680 --> 00:44:59,511
You got any shoelaces?

545
00:44:59,640 --> 00:45:02,234
- What?
- Shoelaces?

546
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:07,557
Anita, get rid of that stuff.
Over here by the cash register.

547
00:45:08,480 --> 00:45:11,358
<i>By the dim glow of a shrouded campfire</i>...

548
00:45:11,480 --> 00:45:15,473
...<i>I saw Rising Star,</i>
<i>and I encountered Sonny Steele himself</i>.

549
00:45:15,600 --> 00:45:16,715
- What?
- What?

550
00:45:16,840 --> 00:45:18,956
- <i>We talked for many hours</i>.
- What?!

551
00:45:19,080 --> 00:45:23,517
<i>As a result of our wide-ranging</i>
<i>conversation, I formed these impressions:</i>

552
00:45:23,760 --> 00:45:28,834
<i>Mr Steele, in my opinion,</i>
<i>did not take the horse for monetary gain</i>...

553
00:45:29,440 --> 00:45:31,396
- Where is he?
- I don't know.

554
00:45:32,120 --> 00:45:34,270
- Where was he?
- I forgot.

555
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:37,915
- How were you able to find him?
- That's my job.

556
00:45:38,040 --> 00:45:40,235
- What did he tell you, Hallie?
- Nothing.

557
00:45:40,360 --> 00:45:45,229
Miss Martin, if you want a story, we could
put you right in the middle of the story.

558
00:45:45,600 --> 00:45:49,354
We could guarantee
that you get first crack at everything.

559
00:45:49,960 --> 00:45:52,190
I've already had first crack at everything.

560
00:45:52,320 --> 00:45:54,595
Suppose we made it exclusive?

561
00:45:54,720 --> 00:45:58,395
How about if we gave you
exclusive footage on the capture?

562
00:45:58,520 --> 00:46:00,795
Oh, when are you planning that?

563
00:46:00,920 --> 00:46:05,755
Wanna tell me about that confrontation
with Steele at the reception, Mr Sears?

564
00:46:06,240 --> 00:46:10,028
- Miss Martin, we could take you to court.
- You could try.

565
00:46:10,280 --> 00:46:14,592
Aiding a felon during the commission of
a felonious act, concealment of a felony...

566
00:46:14,720 --> 00:46:17,075
"Misprision of felony", the law calls it.

567
00:46:17,200 --> 00:46:21,273
You're not the law. If Ampco wants to take
on the First Amendment, be my guest.

568
00:46:21,400 --> 00:46:24,198
That oughta sell
a whole lot of breakfast cereal.

569
00:46:24,320 --> 00:46:27,835
I'll be around,
if you wanna handcuff me later.

570
00:46:34,440 --> 00:46:36,874
- We <i>could</i> take her to court.
- Have her locked up.

571
00:46:37,000 --> 00:46:39,912
And gain what? The last thing
we need is a female martyr.

572
00:46:40,040 --> 00:46:42,998
At least he didn't say anything
about mistreating the horse.

573
00:46:43,120 --> 00:46:45,714
- Do we know that?
- I think she'd have said something.

574
00:46:45,840 --> 00:46:48,957
You "think". It's a chance
we can't afford to take.

575
00:46:50,360 --> 00:46:52,237
Do we have a choice?

576
00:46:52,360 --> 00:46:56,717
We could make sure that if he speaks
to anyone he won't be believed.

577
00:46:57,480 --> 00:46:59,630
Can you get to the media
by the 11 o'clock news?

578
00:47:10,040 --> 00:47:12,838
How the hell did she find him,
we ain't even heard from him?

579
00:47:12,960 --> 00:47:15,599
We sent her over there,
that's how she found him.

580
00:47:15,720 --> 00:47:20,510
Well, she buddied up to me. She tried
to buy me drinks, said she liked my ring...

581
00:47:20,640 --> 00:47:23,916
She liked your ring, she liked
my watch, I liked her eyes...

582
00:47:24,040 --> 00:47:28,192
That's how those people are. They tell
you they're your friend, and they use you.

583
00:47:28,320 --> 00:47:30,151
Well, what are we gonna do?

584
00:47:30,280 --> 00:47:32,999
I don't know about you.
I'm gonna get a bottle of tequila...

585
00:47:33,120 --> 00:47:37,830
...one of those keno girls that can suck the
chrome off a trailer hitch, and kick back.

586
00:47:38,080 --> 00:47:42,596
<i>10.59 here at KLSG in St George,</i>
<i>and here's Harvey Del Rio</i>...

587
00:47:42,720 --> 00:47:47,111
If I could drive sleepin' the way you sleep
standin', boy, we'd have this licked.

588
00:47:47,440 --> 00:47:52,639
<i>In Las Vegas, investigators still have no</i>
<i>leads to the whereabouts of Rising Star,</i>...

589
00:47:52,760 --> 00:47:55,877
...<i>whose ab duction by Sonny Steele</i>
<i>triggered a massive search</i>.

590
00:47:56,000 --> 00:47:59,276
<i>Ampco officials are expressing alarm</i>
<i>over the welfare of the horse</i>.

591
00:47:59,400 --> 00:48:03,279
<i>According to one, Steele has a long history</i>
<i>of alcoholism and drug abuse</i>.

592
00:48:03,400 --> 00:48:07,234
<i>He's appeared in public in an intoxicated</i>
<i>state on several occasions,</i>...

593
00:48:07,360 --> 00:48:09,635
...<i>and has been abusive</i>
<i>to press and public</i>.

594
00:48:09,760 --> 00:48:12,957
<i>They believe if the horse is to survive,</i>
<i>time is of the essence</i>.

595
00:48:31,080 --> 00:48:33,878
Excuse me, Miss Martin?
I'm Charlotta Steele.

596
00:48:36,240 --> 00:48:38,390
- I was married to Sonny.
- Yes, I know.

597
00:48:38,520 --> 00:48:42,195
I don't mean to bother you, but
I was just wonderin' if he was all right.

598
00:48:42,320 --> 00:48:45,278
- He isn't hurt?
- No.

599
00:48:46,520 --> 00:48:52,117
- Are you gonna be seein' him again?
- Well, we haven't made any plans. Why?

600
00:48:53,040 --> 00:48:54,712
Just wonderin'.

601
00:48:55,680 --> 00:48:58,638
- Why do you think he did it?
- I don't know.

602
00:49:00,680 --> 00:49:06,277
He gets ornery. Guess it takes him a long
time to admit he's got a horn in his gut.

603
00:49:07,320 --> 00:49:09,959
What <i>is</i> the horn in his gut, Mrs Steele?

604
00:49:11,840 --> 00:49:15,515
All's I know is he musta had a good
reason, or he woulda been back by now.

605
00:49:15,640 --> 00:49:19,792
He's no thief by nature.
I mean, it takes your breath!

606
00:49:23,200 --> 00:49:26,078
You know, they only said
those bad things about him.

607
00:49:26,200 --> 00:49:30,193
They didn't say what's decent. Even
though it is hard to find it sometimes.

608
00:49:30,320 --> 00:49:32,276
How'd you meet Sonny?

609
00:49:40,320 --> 00:49:42,550
Hallie Martin, please.

610
00:49:51,720 --> 00:49:53,995
- What?
- <i>You alone?</i>

611
00:49:54,800 --> 00:49:57,439
- Who is this?
- Are you alone?

612
00:49:57,560 --> 00:50:00,791
OK, fella, say your dirties. Get it over with.

613
00:50:01,360 --> 00:50:04,113
It's time for another
wide-rangin' conversation.

614
00:50:06,280 --> 00:50:09,033
- <i>Hello?</i>
- Is it you?

615
00:50:09,160 --> 00:50:11,720
Right from the dim glow
of the shrouded campfire.

616
00:50:11,840 --> 00:50:12,795
<i>You maniac!</i>

617
00:50:12,920 --> 00:50:15,115
I broke three nails changing that tyre.

618
00:50:15,360 --> 00:50:17,999
- You want a story?
- Yes.

619
00:50:18,640 --> 00:50:23,555
- Can you leave without anybody knowin'?
- If I can't, I won't come.

620
00:50:25,840 --> 00:50:28,479
- Who saw him?
- Some little shopkeeper in Utah.

621
00:50:28,600 --> 00:50:32,036
Near St George, about five last night.
He must've gotten a vehicle.

622
00:50:32,160 --> 00:50:37,314
So if he stopped for the night he should
be within 150 miles of St George.

623
00:50:37,440 --> 00:50:40,034
- Who knows this?
- The local police are taken care of.

624
00:50:40,160 --> 00:50:42,390
- The press?
- No, not yet, not yet.

625
00:50:42,520 --> 00:50:45,876
- We'll take care of it.
- Can we cover the surrounding towns?

626
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:49,117
Taking care of it now. We'll concentrate
on Liberty and Cedarville.

627
00:50:49,240 --> 00:50:53,392
You and Toland take the jet.
You can organise this from St George.

628
00:50:53,520 --> 00:50:56,353
- If he stopped for the night.
- He must sleep sometimes.

629
00:50:56,480 --> 00:50:58,869
He crossed the state line.
The FBI will want in.

630
00:50:59,000 --> 00:51:02,595
- Can you keep 'em out?
- They already know he's been spotted.

631
00:51:02,720 --> 00:51:07,714
Then get to him first. Tell him we won't
prosecute. Do whatever you have to do.

632
00:51:07,840 --> 00:51:10,115
Just don't let him start up
about the horse.

633
00:51:15,760 --> 00:51:17,910
I'm here!

634
00:51:21,360 --> 00:51:23,351
Hey, I'm here!

635
00:51:23,480 --> 00:51:25,675
I'm alone. No troops.

636
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,639
Come on. Come on.

637
00:51:41,720 --> 00:51:43,870
Oh... Oh, God!

638
00:51:44,000 --> 00:51:46,195
I think I've broken my leg.

639
00:51:48,480 --> 00:51:50,710
What are you gonna do, shoot me?

640
00:52:07,800 --> 00:52:10,155
Here. Get your camera ready.

641
00:52:12,480 --> 00:52:14,072
Uh...

642
00:52:14,200 --> 00:52:17,510
Listen, would you mind standing
over here with that background?

643
00:52:17,640 --> 00:52:20,313
No, this is all right. Right here.

644
00:52:20,440 --> 00:52:23,079
But I think it'd be more dramatic
in front of...

645
00:52:23,200 --> 00:52:27,478
Tell 'em it was dramatic.
You got a colourful imagination.

646
00:52:29,000 --> 00:52:34,120
Listen, I've been driving all night,
and I'm not used to being talked to like...

647
00:52:34,240 --> 00:52:36,629
I'm not used to being called a horse thief.

648
00:52:36,760 --> 00:52:40,070
What do <i>you</i> call
a man who steals horses?

649
00:52:41,040 --> 00:52:43,759
Have you ever seen this horse race?

650
00:52:45,040 --> 00:52:47,759
Have you ever seen... I've seen him run.

651
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:53,994
I saw him stumble and fall back,
and lose his stride, and pick himself up.

652
00:52:54,120 --> 00:52:57,112
I saw him stretch out
when he had <i>nothin'</i> left to give...

653
00:52:57,240 --> 00:53:00,038
...but he found it... somewhere.

654
00:53:00,160 --> 00:53:02,230
And he won.

655
00:53:02,360 --> 00:53:06,069
Lady, that horse is a champion.
He's got a heart the size of a locomotive.

656
00:53:06,200 --> 00:53:11,035
He's got more heart, and more drive,
and more... soul...

657
